04719nam a22007575i 9780231532297DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014011654  a(OCoLC)979754083  a97802315322977 a10.7312/kink167682doi  a(DE-B1597)458394  a(OCoLC)904810772  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPL2419.H57bK56 2014 7aLIT0080102bisacsh04a895.13/5092231 aKinkley, Jeffrey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aVisions of Dystopia in China’s New Historical Novels /cJeffrey Kinkley. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction: Chinese Visions of History and Dystopia -- t2. Discomforts of Temporal Anomie -- t3. Projections of Historical Repetition -- t4. Alienation from the Group -- t5. Anarchy: Social, Moral, and Cosmic -- t6. Conclusion: The End of History, Dystopia, and “New” Historical Novels? -- tList of Chinese Characters -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe depiction of personal and collective suffering in modern Chinese novels differs significantly from standard Communist accounts and many Eastern and Western historical narratives. Writers such as Yu Hua, Su Tong, Wang Anyi, Mo Yan, Han Shaogong, Ge Fei, Li Rui, and Zhang Wei skew and scramble common conceptions of China's modern development, deploying avant-garde narrative techniques from Latin American and Euro-American modernism to project a surprisingly "un-Chinese" dystopian vision and critical view of human culture and ethics.The epic narratives of modern Chinese fiction make rich use of magical realism, surrealism, and unusual treatments of historical time. Also featuring graphic depictions of sex and violence, as well as dark, raunchy comedy, these novels reflect China's recent history re-presenting the overthrow of the monarchy in the early twentieth century and the resulting chaos of revolution and war; the recurring miseries perpetrated by class warfare during the dictatorship of Mao Zedong; and the social dislocations caused by China's industrialization and rise as a global power. This book casts China's highbrow historical novels from the late 1980s to the first decade of the twenty-first century as a distinctively Chinese contribution to the form of the global dystopian novel and, consequently, to global thinking about the interrelations of utopia and dystopia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChinese fictionxHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aChinese fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aChinese fiction. 0aDystopias in literature. 0aHistorical fiction, ChinesexCriticism, interpretation, etc. 0aHistorical fiction, ChinesexHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Chinese.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/kink1676840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231532297423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231532297.jpg  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK